D-n-s configuration.

By default, a container's resolver configuration is generated by the daemon. On a user-defined bridge it points at docker's embedded resolver, and for everything else it falls back to the host's upstream d-n-s. That embedded resolver does three jobs. It resolves other container names on the same user-defined network to their addresses, it resolves any network alias you have assigned, and it forwards everything else upstream.

You can override the defaults in several ways. You can set a custom d-n-s server, set a search domain, or add a static hosts entry that maps a name to a fixed address inside the container, which is handy when you want a name to resolve to a specific address without involving d-n-s at all. You can set the container's hostname. And you can give the container one or more network aliases, alternate names it can be reached by on its network.

Network aliases are more powerful than they first appear. A container can answer to several names on a network, and, importantly, multiple containers can share the same alias, which lets the embedded resolver round-robin between them. That gives you a simple form of load distribution by name, without any extra infrastructure, just from the way the resolver hands back addresses for a shared alias.
